## Setting Type 1: Prong Solitaire — The Foundation of Oval Settings

The prong solitaire is the reference standard for ring settings for oval diamond rings. All other settings are measured against it. It maximizes visible face-up area, maximizes elongation, minimizes setting cost, and focuses all attention on the diamond.

### 4-Prong vs 6-Prong: The Decision That Matters Most

**4-prong oval diamond ring:** Four claw prongs at four contact points. For an oval, these typically fall near the east-west sides plus two angled positions toward the tips. Cleaner look — less metal visible. The downsides: tip protection is indirect, and the four-prong configuration on an oval can look slightly asymmetric from certain viewing angles.

**Oval diamond with 6 prongs:** Six claw prongs provide direct tip-to-tip coverage. The 6 prong setting for oval diamond specifically protects both long-axis ends. The data speaks: the Classic Six-Prong has 1,894 reviews vs 1,643 for the Four Prong, despite being $130 more. Buyers who research the difference upgrade to the six-prong setting.

**Claw prongs for oval diamonds:** Claw prongs — the tapered, pointed metal projections that grip the girdle — are the standard prong type for oval settings. The tapered point minimizes metal coverage over the diamond's crown and allows maximum light entry. Blue Nile's standard solitaire settings use claw prong designs by default. "Claw" is the UK/Australian term; US buyers typically say "prong."

