## Setting Type 5: Vintage and Art-Deco — Milgrain and Engraving

Vintage oval diamond settings draw from four historical eras: Art Deco (1920–1935, geometric and angular), Edwardian/Lace Bridge (1901–1910, filigree and lace-like metalwork), Art Nouveau/Romantic (1890–1910, organic curves and floral motifs), and Victorian Halo (1837–1901, ornate and layered). On Blue Nile, all vintage settings are vintage-inspired — new rings with period-appropriate decorative details. Genuine pre-1940 antique oval settings are only available from estate dealers.

**The defining element of vintage oval settings — milgrain:** The milgrain bead border running along the edge of vintage settings is a row of tiny metal balls carved into the metal surface. It adds tactile and visual texture without changing the setting's structural profile. It costs almost nothing to produce but creates the strongest possible signal of vintage craftsmanship. For buyers who want a "vintage" oval diamond ring, milgrain is the most cost-efficient way to achieve that aesthetic.

**Why vintage settings work especially well with oval diamonds:** The oval's soft, curved outline is inherently more romantic and period-appropriate than the sharp geometry of a princess or emerald cut. Milgrain borders, engraved shanks, and scrollwork details reinforce the oval's curves rather than fighting them. An oval diamond in a vintage setting looks like it belongs together.

