## Setting Type 6: Bezel — Protective, Minimal, Modern

A bezel setting surrounds the oval's entire girdle with a continuous metal wall — no prongs, no exposed edges. It is the most protective and snag-free setting for an oval diamond. It is also the setting that most significantly changes the oval's visual presentation, reducing apparent face-up area by 15–22%.

**The full bezel trade-off for oval:** The metal wall covers the oval's girdle edges — including the long-axis tips that provide most of the oval's elongation advantage. For a round diamond, losing 15–22% of face-up area is barely noticeable — you see a slightly smaller circle. For an oval, the bezel specifically compresses the ends that make the oval visually distinctive. Evaluate this trade-off consciously before choosing a bezel for an oval diamond.

