## Setting Type 7: East-West and Compass — The Directional Alternative

An east-west oval diamond ring rotates the stone 90° from the traditional north-south orientation. The long axis runs across the width of the finger instead of along its length. This is a contemporary, architectural choice.

**East-west advantages:** Immediately distinct from every other ring on the hand. Tends to read as "modern and considered" rather than traditional. The stone may appear slightly wider on the finger, which some wearers prefer. The [East West Solitaire at $1,050](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/east-west-solitaire-in-14k-yellow-gold-item-193755?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) has only 7 reviews — a rare and unconventional choice.

**East-west trade-off:** The finger-elongating effect that makes oval diamonds uniquely flattering is completely eliminated. If finger elongation is your reason for choosing oval, the east-west orientation defeats that purpose entirely. The [Solitaire Compass Set at $1,045](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/solitaire-compass-set-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-item-195395?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (107 reviews) is a compromise — prongs at all four cardinal points, holding the oval at a slight north-south lean rather than a full 90° rotation.

